00:12:41,994 --> 00:12:46,232
- And over here, we have samples
taken from human subjects,

262
00:12:47,633 --> 00:12:49,201
to study the relative
abundance of Bacillus Virilis

263
00:12:49,235 --> 00:12:51,270
among more commonly
found bacteria.

264
00:12:51,303 --> 00:12:55,407
- So this new hard-to-kill
bacteria is found on humans?

265
00:12:55,441 --> 00:12:57,176
- It's not dangerous
in the concentrations

266
00:12:57,209 --> 00:12:59,145
that we find it in, but
if it continues to grow,

267
00:12:59,178 --> 00:13:01,046
it could be a problem.

268
00:13:01,080 --> 00:13:02,114
- Would you like
the latest results?

269
00:13:02,148 --> 00:13:04,083
- Hi, I'm Caroline.

270
00:13:04,116 --> 00:13:04,884
Mint?
- There's no eating

271
00:13:04,917 --> 00:13:05,818
in the lab.

272
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:08,821
- What do you do here?

273
00:13:08,854 --> 00:13:10,556
- I'm Dr Wolfe's grad student.

274
00:13:10,589 --> 00:13:14,827
- Oh, so how long have you
been mentored by Dr Wolfe?

275
00:13:15,494 --> 00:13:16,562
- Ellen, results?

276
00:13:16,595 --> 00:13:18,030
- 21.5% relative abundance.

277
00:13:18,063 --> 00:13:18,864
- Shit.

278
00:13:20,232 --> 00:13:24,236
Increase the triclocarbon
by two percent.

279
00:13:24,270 --> 00:13:26,305
- Ellen, how does
it make you feel

280
00:13:26,338 --> 00:13:28,474
when Dr Wolfe is short with you?

281
00:13:28,507 --> 00:13:30,843
- How does it what?

282
00:13:30,876 --> 00:13:31,777
- Swab her.

283
00:13:36,916 --> 00:13:37,816
- What's happening?

284
00:13:37,850 --> 00:13:40,719
- I'm including you in my study.

285
00:13:40,753 --> 00:13:43,088
- I'm sensing some hostility.

286
00:13:43,122 --> 00:13:45,024
I know that I may seem
like an intrusion,

287
00:13:45,057 --> 00:13:47,259
but I am here to help you.

288
00:13:48,294 --> 00:13:49,762
- What's going on?

289
00:13:49,795 --> 00:13:52,865
- Some sort of extreme
behavior modification therapy.

290
00:13:52,898 --> 00:13:54,967
- And we get to watch?

291
00:13:55,000 --> 00:13:58,003
(soft guitar music)

292
00:14:03,342 --> 00:14:04,243
- Hi.
- Hi.

293
00:14:05,945 --> 00:14:08,781
- Wow, interesting day.
- Mommy!

294
00:14:09,815 --> 00:14:12,351
- Okay, Mommy has a project.

295
00:14:12,384 --> 00:14:14,086
So let's go make
dinner while she works.

296
00:14:14,119 --> 00:14:16,088
- [Maggie] What's going on?

297
00:14:16,121 --> 00:14:19,758
- I met a woman who
really needs my help.

298
00:14:19,792 --> 00:14:22,795
(soft guitar music)

299
00:14:28,867 --> 00:14:30,836
- [Serena] She started it!

300
00:14:35,140 --> 00:14:38,010
(knocking on door)

301
00:14:43,882 --> 00:14:47,353
(knocking on door)

302
00:14:47,386 --> 00:14:48,187
- Uh!

303
00:14:49,521 --> 00:14:50,389
- Morning!

304
00:14:50,422 --> 00:14:51,724
Coffee?

305
00:14:51,757 --> 00:14:52,791
- Did someone else die?

306
00:14:52,825 --> 00:14:54,393
- Nice PJs.

307
00:14:54,426 --> 00:14:55,461
- Did I die?

308
00:14:55,494 --> 00:14:56,495
Is this hell?

309
00:14:56,528 --> 00:14:57,730
- Lovely home.

310
00:14:58,864 --> 00:15:01,033
I wanted to get our day
off to a good start.

311
00:15:01,066 --> 00:15:02,901
- How did you get
into my building?

312
00:15:02,935 --> 00:15:05,604
- I buzzed and buzzed,
but you didn't answer.

313
00:15:05,638 --> 00:15:06,872
Carl let me in.

314
00:15:06,906 --> 00:15:07,840
- Who the hell is Carl?

315
00:15:07,873 --> 00:15:09,008
- Your building manager.

316
00:15:09,041 --> 00:15:10,609
He is a sweet guy.

317
00:15:10,643 --> 00:15:12,444
- I don't understand
why you're in my home.

318
00:15:12,478 --> 00:15:13,846
Is this legal?

319
00:15:13,879 --> 00:15:15,347
- When I mentioned that
I would be shadowing you,

320
00:15:15,381 --> 00:15:17,716
I didn't just mean at work.

321
00:15:19,351 --> 00:15:20,586
(phone ringing)

322
00:15:20,619 --> 00:15:21,887
- [Operator] 911, what
is your emergency?

323
00:15:21,920 --> 00:15:23,622
- Yes, I'd like to
report an intruder.

324
00:15:23,656 --> 00:15:25,090
Her name is...

325
00:15:25,124 --> 00:15:26,992
What's your name again?

326
00:15:28,694 --> 00:15:31,263
Caroline Sanders, PhD.

327
00:15:31,297 --> 00:15:33,065
She's in the soft
sciences, though.

328
00:15:33,098 --> 00:15:34,166
- [Operator] You
know the intruder?

329
00:15:34,199 --> 00:15:35,834
- May I?

330
00:15:35,868 --> 00:15:36,902
Hi!

331
00:15:36,935 --> 00:15:38,637
I promise to help her
become the kind of person

332
00:15:38,671 --> 00:15:40,439
who respects your time.

333
00:15:40,472 --> 00:15:42,107
Thank you so much for
your brave service

334
00:15:42,141 --> 00:15:44,677
to the people of Los Angeles.

335
00:15:45,978 --> 00:15:49,682
Why don't you get ready and
we'll drive to work together?

336
00:15:49,715 --> 00:15:51,450
Thank you for showing
me your apartment

337
00:15:51,483 --> 00:15:53,085
and giving me a ride.

338
00:15:53,118 --> 00:15:55,688
- You showed up unannounced
and insisted I drive you.

339
00:15:55,721 --> 00:15:57,022
- When a colleague
says thank you,

340
00:15:57,056 --> 00:15:59,992
a simple, you're
welcome, goes a long way.

341
00:16:00,025 --> 00:16:01,627
- I called the police on you.

342
00:16:01,660 --> 00:16:04,797
That's the definition
of not welcome.

343
00:16:04,830 --> 00:16:07,166
- You're very concerned
with being right.

344
00:16:07,199 --> 00:16:08,967
- Is that a bad overall
goal? (phone ringing)

345
00:16:09,001 --> 00:16:10,369
- It makes it difficult to form

346
00:16:10,402 --> 00:16:12,204
deeper relationships
with people.

347
00:16:12,237 --> 00:16:13,539
- [Don] Serena?

348
00:16:13,572 --> 00:16:17,042
- Don, I woke up with a
malignant parasitic cyst

349
00:16:17,076 --> 00:16:19,011
called a sensitivity coach.

350
00:16:19,044 --> 00:16:20,346
- Hi, Dr Pierson.

351
00:16:20,379 --> 00:16:21,914
- You know how close I
am to a breakthrough.

352
00:16:21,947 --> 00:16:23,582
How am I supposed to
get any work done?

353
00:16:23,615 --> 00:16:25,417
This has thrown me
completely off-kilter.

354
00:16:25,451 --> 00:16:28,187
- [Don] Serena, if you
want to keep your job,

355
00:16:28,220 --> 00:16:29,755
you have to complete
this training.

356
00:16:29,788 --> 00:16:32,191
- Can they really blame
me for Laura's death?

357
00:16:32,224 --> 00:16:33,992
Maybe she had a
chemical imbalance?

358
00:16:34,026 --> 00:16:35,227
Was she on medication?

359
00:16:35,260 --> 00:16:37,029
(phone clicking)

360
00:16:37,062 --> 00:16:38,831
Don?

361
00:16:38,864 --> 00:16:40,599
- You have a lovely apartment.

362
00:16:40,632 --> 00:16:44,036
I noticed you don't have any
photos of family and friends.

363
00:16:44,069 --> 00:16:46,805
- Why are people so
obsessed with photos?

364
00:16:46,839 --> 00:16:49,108
Don't they know what
their children look like?

365
00:16:49,141 --> 00:16:52,411
- This is my partner Sarah
and my daughter Maggie.

366
00:16:52,444 --> 00:16:56,181
Photos help me keep
my loved ones with me.

367
00:16:56,215 --> 00:16:57,750
- I was married once.

368
00:16:57,783 --> 00:16:59,418
In college.

369
00:16:59,451 --> 00:17:01,820
It ended after a year.

370
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:02,955
- I'm sorry you
went through that.

371
00:17:02,988 --> 00:17:03,822
(tires screeching)

372
00:17:03,856 --> 00:17:04,857
- What the hell?

373
00:17:04,890 --> 00:17:06,925
Did your mother drop you?

374
00:17:06,959 --> 00:17:08,193
- Just kidding!

375
00:17:08,227 --> 00:17:10,162
We're sure you had a perfectly
good reason to do that.

376
00:17:10,195 --> 00:17:14,333
We're going to give you
the benefit of the doubt.

377
00:17:17,202 --> 00:17:19,705
(quirky music)

378
00:17:25,711 --> 00:17:27,312
- People are transferring
to different labs.

379
00:17:27,346 --> 00:17:29,982
They say they don't want
to work for you anymore.

380
00:17:30,015 --> 00:17:31,316
Hey, that's mine!

381
00:17:34,420 --> 00:17:36,455
- [Caroline] That's
a lot to take in.

382
00:17:36,488 --> 00:17:38,390
How's that make you feel?

383
00:17:38,424 --> 00:17:39,191
- Fine.

384
00:17:39,224 --> 00:17:41,226
(drill buzzing)

385
00:17:41,260 --> 00:17:43,062
I have wanted to work
on a project like this

386
00:17:43,095 --> 00:17:44,196
my entire career.

387
00:17:44,229 --> 00:17:46,231
It was not easy
to get my own lab.

388
00:17:46,265 --> 00:17:48,801
(tape snapping)

389
00:17:48,834 --> 00:17:50,069
People belittle my research.

390
00:17:50,102 --> 00:17:52,171
They say I'm making
hand sanitizer,

391
00:17:52,204 --> 00:17:55,174
but antibiotic
resistance is dangerous.

392
00:17:55,207 --> 00:17:58,110
I may not be curing cancer,
but I am helping people.

393
00:17:58,143 --> 00:17:59,078
(drill buzzing) Hey!

394
00:17:59,111 --> 00:18:00,279
Could you just...

395
00:18:00,312 --> 00:18:02,448
Do you have to do
that right now?

396
00:18:02,481 --> 00:18:03,916
- Just doing my job.

397
00:18:03,949 --> 00:18:07,252
- Thank you for taking
such pride in your work.

398
00:18:07,286 --> 00:18:08,554
- You're welcome.

399
00:18:11,023 --> 00:18:13,325
- Serena, you study bacteria.

400
00:18:13,358 --> 00:18:15,327
I study human behavior.

401
00:18:15,360 --> 00:18:19,598
How do you determine how to
kill drug-resistant bacteria?

402
00:18:20,599 --> 00:18:22,134
- Perpetual
observation, hypothesis,

403
00:18:22,167 --> 00:18:24,169
and then methodical testing
until I get a favorable result.

404
00:18:24,203 --> 00:18:27,172
- And I'm going to observe
you in your environment,

405
00:18:27,206 --> 00:18:30,075
generate a hypothesis as to
why you are the way you are,

406
00:18:30,109 --> 00:18:32,845
though I have a few
ideas, and work with you

407
00:18:32,878 --> 00:18:35,347
to mitigate your behavior
and neutralize your effect

408
00:18:35,380 --> 00:18:39,351
on the environment until
I get a favorable result.

409
00:18:39,384 --> 00:18:43,355
- Did you just liken me
to a pathogenic bacterium?

410
00:18:43,388 --> 00:18:45,324
Oh, now you're done.

411
00:18:45,357 --> 00:18:47,459
Thank you, thank you so much.

412
00:18:47,493 --> 00:18:49,428
- You're welcome.

413
00:18:49,461 --> 00:18:52,030
- What was so fucking important?

414
00:18:57,169 --> 00:19:00,506
How quickly can you even
get one of these made?

415
00:19:00,539 --> 00:19:02,007
- It's beautifully done.

416
00:19:02,040 --> 00:19:02,774
- Got it.

417
00:19:08,780 --> 00:19:13,018
- Can you succeed in your
research without a staff?

418
00:19:14,419 --> 00:19:17,623
- Okay, so that's definitely
university property.

419
00:19:27,399 --> 00:19:28,367
Okay.

420
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:29,201
People!

421
00:19:30,469 --> 00:19:32,971
I know I can be a bit abrasive.

422
00:19:34,640 --> 00:19:37,943
And I'm sorry for
the way I've behaved.

423
00:19:39,411 --> 00:19:43,615
I'm receiving help and
learning to be more sensitive.

424
00:19:46,618 --> 00:19:47,953
Please stay.

425
00:19:47,986 --> 00:19:48,787
I...

426
00:19:50,622 --> 00:19:51,957
I believe in the
work that we're doing

427
00:19:51,990 --> 00:19:53,792
and I know you do too.

428
00:20:12,010 --> 00:20:12,811
What now?

429
00:20:13,745 --> 00:20:15,247
- We get to work.

430
00:20:17,216 --> 00:20:19,418
Welcome to our safe space.

431
00:20:24,590 --> 00:20:26,458
Let's start with the basics.

432
00:20:26,491 --> 00:20:28,827
When someone gives you a lab
result that you don't like,

433
00:20:28,860 --> 00:20:32,564
try saying thank you
instead of swearing at them.

434
00:20:32,598 --> 00:20:36,568
- So you want me to
thank someone for
giving me shitty news?

435
00:20:36,835 --> 00:20:38,570
- It's acknowledging
the effort it took

436
00:20:38,604 --> 00:20:40,706
to give you that news.

437
00:20:40,739 --> 00:20:44,376
- Hey, Caroline, your
kitten has feline AIDS.

438
00:20:44,409 --> 00:20:47,746
- I don't have a kitten, but
thank you for that information.

439
00:20:47,779 --> 00:20:49,848
Let's do a quick role-play.

440
00:20:49,881 --> 00:20:51,883
I'll be a colleague you
find really annoying.

441
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:53,552
- Tough to imagine.

442
00:20:53,585 --> 00:20:56,588
- Dr Wolfe, is it okay if I
leave work early tomorrow?

443
00:20:56,622 --> 00:20:58,590
My boyfriend's taking
me out and I'd rather go

444
00:20:58,624 --> 00:21:02,261
on a date with my boyfriend
than make hand sanitizer.

445
00:21:02,294 --> 00:21:05,430
Now, you respond in
a respectful way.

446
00:21:06,298 --> 00:21:09,001
- I'm not responding to that.

447
00:21:09,034 --> 00:21:10,302
- I feel--

448
00:21:10,335 --> 00:21:12,771
- Why can't I just say
what I want to say?

449
00:21:12,804 --> 00:21:14,673
- If you begin by using, I feel,

450
00:21:14,706 --> 00:21:16,642
the person's less
likely to be offended.

451
00:21:16,675 --> 00:21:18,977
You're simply stating
how you personally feel.

452
00:21:19,011 --> 00:21:21,713
- Okay, I feel that's retarded.

453
00:21:23,482 --> 00:21:25,651
- Many people find
that word offensive.

454
00:21:25,684 --> 00:21:27,619
- But it's what I feel.

455
00:21:28,720 --> 00:21:29,988
- Get it all out.

456
00:21:37,229 --> 00:21:38,263
That's okay.

457
00:21:38,296 --> 00:21:39,297
I have more.

458
00:21:44,069 --> 00:21:47,205
Let's talk about your parents.

459
00:21:47,239 --> 00:21:49,808
- Should I lie on a couch
and recover a memory

460
00:21:49,841 --> 00:21:52,210
of being fondled by my uncle?

461
00:21:52,244 --> 00:21:53,812
- Were you?

462
00:21:53,845 --> 00:21:54,846
That's a joke.

463
00:21:54,880 --> 00:21:56,281
Unless you were.

464
00:21:57,883 --> 00:22:00,385
I'm trying to figure out why
your defenses are so high.

465
00:22:00,419 --> 00:22:01,853
- My defenses?

466
00:22:01,887 --> 00:22:05,057
- Your quick temper,
condescension, your need to say

467
00:22:05,090 --> 00:22:07,092
every insult that
pops into your brain.

468
00:22:07,125 --> 00:22:08,894
- Not every insult.

469
00:22:08,927 --> 00:22:11,930
- These are your
defense mechanisms.

470
00:22:12,964 --> 00:22:16,201
What are you protecting
yourself from?

471
00:22:17,369 --> 00:22:20,038
Let's discuss your triggers.

472
00:22:20,072 --> 00:22:23,075
What gets you really annoyed?

473
00:22:23,108 --> 00:22:24,710
What do you hate?

474
00:22:24,743 --> 00:22:26,645
- I get to talk
about what I hate?

475
00:22:26,678 --> 00:22:27,779
- Of course.

476
00:22:27,813 --> 00:22:29,614
- And I can say whatever I want?

477
00:22:29,648 --> 00:22:30,449
- Please.

478
00:22:31,917 --> 00:22:32,684
- Okay.

479
00:22:34,953 --> 00:22:36,688
I hate being wrong.

480
00:22:38,790 --> 00:22:41,760
I hate it when I'm right
but people think I'm wrong.

481
00:22:41,793 --> 00:22:43,462
I hate when a person is
wrong but they insist,

482
00:22:43,495 --> 00:22:46,498
despite all available
evidence, that they're right.

483
00:22:46,531 --> 00:22:48,934
I hate that it's considered
rude to correct people.

484
00:22:48,967 --> 00:22:50,969
They should just say thank you.

485
00:22:51,002 --> 00:22:53,171
I hate when people get
recognition they don't deserve.

486
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:54,806
I detest small talk.

487
00:22:54,840 --> 00:22:56,108
I don't want to talk
about the weather.

488
00:22:56,141 --> 00:22:57,709
I don't want to
talk about traffic.

489
00:22:57,743 --> 00:23:00,278
If you think you have some
special, magical route

490
00:23:00,312 --> 00:23:01,980
to get to work, I don't
want to hear about it.

491
00:23:02,013 --> 00:23:03,715
It's probably not that good.

492
00:23:03,749 --> 00:23:06,885
I hate when people inflict
their personal problems onto me.

493
00:23:06,918 --> 00:23:10,122
I hate when people bring their
children or pets into work

494
00:23:10,155 --> 00:23:12,190
or force you to look
at vacation photos.

495
00:23:12,224 --> 00:23:15,460
I also hate when women
put on that voice

496
00:23:15,494 --> 00:23:19,698
when they speak to or
about children or animals.

497
00:23:20,999 --> 00:23:22,634
I don't want to hear about
your hobbies, marriages,

498
00:23:22,667 --> 00:23:25,003
where you bought a particular
item, whether it was on sale.

499
00:23:25,036 --> 00:23:27,539
I hate when people
listen to music so loudly

500
00:23:27,572 --> 00:23:29,708
that you can hear it
through their headphones.

501
00:23:29,741 --> 00:23:31,977
I hate when people make up
abbreviations for things

502
00:23:32,010 --> 00:23:34,012
and use them in regular speech.

503
00:23:34,045 --> 00:23:36,081
I hate emoticons; I never
understand what they mean.

504
00:23:36,114 --> 00:23:38,049
I hate overzealous huggers.

505
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:39,451
I hate the word bro.

506
00:23:39,484 --> 00:23:42,020
I hate the overuse
of exclamation marks.

507
00:23:42,053 --> 00:23:45,223
I hate when I'm parallel
parking and the car behind me

508
00:23:45,257 --> 00:23:48,860
honks like they have no idea
why I'm not driving forward

509
00:23:48,894 --> 00:23:53,098
as though they've never
parked in their entire life.

510
00:23:54,666 --> 00:23:56,401
I hate the color purple,
not the book or the movie,

511
00:23:56,435 --> 00:23:57,903
just the actual color.

512
00:23:57,936 --> 00:24:00,105
I hate proposal videos.

513
00:24:00,138 --> 00:24:01,673
I hate flash mobs.

514
00:24:01,706 --> 00:24:04,075
I hate the phrase baby bump.

515
00:24:04,109 --> 00:24:05,577
I hate that's what
she said jokes.

516
00:24:05,610 --> 00:24:08,113
I hate when men use erection
metaphors to describe

517
00:24:08,146 --> 00:24:10,315
something that they
really like, for example,

518
00:24:10,348 --> 00:24:13,919
I have a total hard on
for this deep-dish pizza.

519
00:24:13,952 --> 00:24:15,487
I hate deep-dish pizza.

