00:24:15,520 --> 00:24:17,823
I also hate mini cupcakes.

521
00:24:17,856 --> 00:24:20,325
I hate when people speak
in random foreign accents

522
00:24:20,358 --> 00:24:21,860
like it's inherently funny.

523
00:24:21,893 --> 00:24:25,030
Sounding vaguely
British isn't funny.

524
00:24:29,367 --> 00:24:30,602
- Thank you, Serena.

525
00:24:30,635 --> 00:24:32,137
That was a good start.

526
00:24:32,170 --> 00:24:32,971
- I could keep going.

527
00:24:33,004 --> 00:24:33,972
- No, no.

528
00:24:34,005 --> 00:24:35,407
That was plenty.

529
00:24:41,079 --> 00:24:43,014
Today wasn't so bad was it?

530
00:24:43,048 --> 00:24:43,849
- Yes?

531
00:24:44,783 --> 00:24:47,319
- [Ethan] Serena, it's Ethan.

532
00:24:47,352 --> 00:24:48,720
- Oh.

533
00:24:48,753 --> 00:24:50,021
Hey.

534
00:24:50,055 --> 00:24:51,089
- Who's this?

535
00:24:51,122 --> 00:24:52,424
- None of your business.

536
00:24:52,457 --> 00:24:53,658
- [Ethan] Am I on speaker?

537
00:24:53,692 --> 00:24:54,826
- I'm driving.

538
00:24:54,860 --> 00:24:56,094
- [Ethan] Is someone
else with you?

539
00:24:56,127 --> 00:24:57,028
- Hello!

540
00:24:57,062 --> 00:24:59,698
I'm Caroline, who's this?

541
00:24:59,731 --> 00:25:01,433
- [Ethan] Ethan,
Serena's brother.

542
00:25:01,466 --> 00:25:02,567
- Sorry to interrupt.

543
00:25:02,601 --> 00:25:04,936
- Can I call you back later?

544
00:25:04,970 --> 00:25:05,871
- [Ethan] Sure.

545
00:25:05,904 --> 00:25:07,405
- Great thanks, bye.
- I need to talk to you.

546
00:25:07,439 --> 00:25:08,206
- You have a brother?

547
00:25:08,240 --> 00:25:10,208
- Half-brother.

548
00:25:10,242 --> 00:25:14,079
- Hmm, he sounded
like a teen in crisis.

549
00:25:14,112 --> 00:25:15,947
How old were you
when he was born?

550
00:25:15,981 --> 00:25:16,748
- 17.

551
00:25:16,781 --> 00:25:18,283
I barely know him.

552
00:25:18,316 --> 00:25:20,285
- Your parents are divorced?

553
00:25:20,318 --> 00:25:24,155
- My father left and
then my mother met Glenn.

554
00:25:24,189 --> 00:25:27,325
- That must have
been hard for you.

555
00:25:27,359 --> 00:25:30,495
Where do you go to
unwind after work?

556
00:25:32,330 --> 00:25:35,133
- [Actor] Oh, when
did you get it?

557
00:25:36,234 --> 00:25:37,302
Okay.

558
00:25:38,236 --> 00:25:39,137
So?

559
00:25:39,170 --> 00:25:40,538
- [Moviegoer] You tell him.

560
00:25:40,572 --> 00:25:41,373
- Shh.

561
00:25:43,041 --> 00:25:44,142
- [Moviegoer] She's
too pretty for him.

562
00:25:44,175 --> 00:25:45,443
- [Moviegoer] Mm-hm.

563
00:25:45,477 --> 00:25:46,878
- As much as I love your
brilliant commentary,

564
00:25:46,912 --> 00:25:48,446
do you think you could
keep it to yourself?

565
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:49,481
- Serena.

566
00:25:49,514 --> 00:25:50,382
- It's fine.

567
00:25:50,415 --> 00:25:52,884
This happens all the time.

568
00:25:52,918 --> 00:25:54,452
- [Moviegoer] I'm just
trying to watch the movie.

569
00:25:54,486 --> 00:25:57,656
- Could you watch it
with your mouth closed?

570
00:25:57,689 --> 00:25:59,090
- [Usher] Ma'am.

571
00:26:00,058 --> 00:26:01,793
- What's happening?

572
00:26:01,826 --> 00:26:03,028
- We have to go now.

573
00:26:03,061 --> 00:26:03,962
- What?

574
00:26:03,995 --> 00:26:05,797
- We're being kicked out.

575
00:26:05,830 --> 00:26:06,598
Come on.

576
00:26:12,370 --> 00:26:14,239
- Why did you engage with her?

577
00:26:14,272 --> 00:26:15,840
- She started it.

578
00:26:15,874 --> 00:26:17,242
She shouldn't have been talking.

579
00:26:17,275 --> 00:26:20,545
- Yes, but you
always have a choice.

580
00:26:20,578 --> 00:26:22,247
Would you rather
be right or not get

581
00:26:22,280 --> 00:26:24,215
kicked out of the theater?

582
00:26:24,249 --> 00:26:28,453
I mean, when was the last time
you saw the end of a movie?

583
00:26:30,288 --> 00:26:33,425
(buzzer buzzing)

584
00:26:33,458 --> 00:26:37,095
Happy second week of
sensitivity training!

585
00:26:43,635 --> 00:26:44,836
Don't do that!

586
00:26:46,037 --> 00:26:47,339
Come on, open it.

587
00:26:54,846 --> 00:26:56,247
Do you like him?

588
00:26:56,281 --> 00:26:58,450
- I don't understand
what's happening.

589
00:26:58,483 --> 00:27:00,018
- [Caroline] Caring
for another creature

590
00:27:00,051 --> 00:27:01,820
is part of your training.

591
00:27:01,853 --> 00:27:03,355
Haven't you ever had a pet?

592
00:27:03,388 --> 00:27:04,489
- This isn't a pet.

593
00:27:04,522 --> 00:27:08,326
This is a cesspool for
pathogenic bacteria.

594
00:27:08,360 --> 00:27:09,961
- But isn't he cute?

595
00:27:14,466 --> 00:27:16,301
- [Serena] Most small
turtles are illegal.

596
00:27:16,334 --> 00:27:17,936
They're smuggled in
from other countries

597
00:27:17,969 --> 00:27:21,373
and they destroy the ecosystems
of our ponds and rivers.

598
00:27:21,406 --> 00:27:23,308
- This isn't the
illegal kind of turtle.

599
00:27:23,341 --> 00:27:26,478
He's the adorable
pet kind of turtle.

600
00:27:28,380 --> 00:27:30,682
- It probably has Salmonella.

601
00:27:31,583 --> 00:27:33,051
- You like bacteria.

602
00:27:33,084 --> 00:27:36,554
It'll give you two
something to talk about.

603
00:27:36,588 --> 00:27:38,523
- [Serena] I really have
to care for this thing?

604
00:27:38,556 --> 00:27:41,326
- You have to give him a
name, give him a nice home.

605
00:27:41,359 --> 00:27:44,195
Think about him when
you're not around.

606
00:27:44,229 --> 00:27:46,264
It's all part of being a person.

607
00:27:46,297 --> 00:27:49,067
- First, I'm going to
test him for Salmonella.

608
00:27:49,100 --> 00:27:53,304
- Okay, remember what we've
practiced about taking a breath

609
00:27:54,139 --> 00:27:56,374
if you don't like what you hear.

610
00:27:56,408 --> 00:27:57,442
And.

611
00:28:00,145 --> 00:28:02,414
Here's your new stress ball.

612
00:28:02,447 --> 00:28:03,882
It's a molecule.

613
00:28:04,983 --> 00:28:05,884
Squeeze it!

614
00:28:14,459 --> 00:28:15,760
- Morning, Ellen.

615
00:28:16,961 --> 00:28:19,064
- Good morning, Dr Wolfe.

616
00:28:19,097 --> 00:28:21,866
- How was your
evening last night?

617
00:28:24,569 --> 00:28:25,503
- It was good, actually, I--

618
00:28:25,537 --> 00:28:26,604
- Wonderful.

619
00:28:26,638 --> 00:28:28,473
Do you have the results
from last night's tests?

620
00:28:28,506 --> 00:28:29,607
- Yeah, it was 26%.

621
00:28:29,641 --> 00:28:30,508
- Shit.

622
00:28:30,542 --> 00:28:32,510
A three percent increase?

623
00:28:35,013 --> 00:28:38,683
I mean, okay, thank you
for that information.

624
00:28:40,251 --> 00:28:43,655
- Dr Wolfe, could you
take a look at this?

625
00:28:48,059 --> 00:28:49,260
- Interesting.

626
00:28:50,728 --> 00:28:52,297
Thanks for pointing this out.

627
00:28:52,330 --> 00:28:54,232
- Dr Wolfe, I had an idea
I wanted to show you.

628
00:28:54,265 --> 00:28:55,166
What if we--

629
00:28:55,200 --> 00:28:56,067
- No, that wouldn't work.

630
00:28:56,101 --> 00:28:58,570
Here, test this for Salmonella.

631
00:29:00,038 --> 00:29:00,839
- Oh.

632
00:29:05,243 --> 00:29:07,712
- I think it's safe to say
that didn't go very well.

633
00:29:07,745 --> 00:29:09,481
- The virilis count should
be decreasing by now.

634
00:29:09,514 --> 00:29:11,082
I don't know what I'm missing.

635
00:29:11,116 --> 00:29:15,019
- We need to discuss how you
just spoke to Ellen out there.

636
00:29:16,554 --> 00:29:18,523
- I'm sorry I didn't play
nice at your tea party,

637
00:29:18,556 --> 00:29:22,560
but I'm trying to prevent
a public health crisis.

638
00:29:23,761 --> 00:29:25,063
This is science,
not little league.

639
00:29:25,096 --> 00:29:28,700
- Positive reinforcement
encourages productivity.

640
00:29:28,733 --> 00:29:30,568
- Are you even a real person

641
00:29:30,602 --> 00:29:33,004
or are you a schizophrenic
hallucination?

642
00:29:33,037 --> 00:29:35,106
Should I be on medication?

643
00:29:35,140 --> 00:29:36,007
- Probably.

644
00:29:38,643 --> 00:29:41,212
(playful music)

645
00:30:25,757 --> 00:30:27,525
- Thanks for letting
me drive today.

646
00:30:27,559 --> 00:30:29,227
(toy squeaking)

647
00:30:29,260 --> 00:30:30,562
- [Maggie] Hello!

648
00:30:30,595 --> 00:30:31,796
- [Caroline] Maggie,
what did I tell you

649
00:30:31,829 --> 00:30:33,264
about throwing your toys?

650
00:30:33,298 --> 00:30:35,400
- Why is there a small
child in the vehicle?

651
00:30:35,433 --> 00:30:38,570
- Serena, this is my
little monster, Maggie.

652
00:30:38,603 --> 00:30:40,405
Maggie, this is Serena.

653
00:30:40,438 --> 00:30:41,439
We work together.

654
00:30:41,472 --> 00:30:42,774
- Not exactly.

655
00:30:42,807 --> 00:30:45,977
- Do you do sex
people her past meat?

656
00:30:46,010 --> 00:30:49,314
- That's how she says
sexual harassment.

657
00:30:49,347 --> 00:30:50,748
- Does she have a
learning disability?

658
00:30:50,782 --> 00:30:52,884
- No, she's just five.

659
00:30:52,917 --> 00:30:54,552
- I'm almost six!

660
00:30:54,586 --> 00:30:57,121
And I'm going to have the
biggest birthday party ever!

661
00:30:57,155 --> 00:30:58,423
- Sarah had an early meeting

662
00:30:58,456 --> 00:31:00,959
so I'm driving Maggie
to school today.

663
00:31:00,992 --> 00:31:04,362
- It's not going to be
a long drive, is it?

664
00:31:04,395 --> 00:31:05,997
- This could be an
opportunity for you

665
00:31:06,030 --> 00:31:08,299
to work on your hostility
toward children.

666
00:31:08,333 --> 00:31:09,934
- You don't like kids?

667
00:31:09,968 --> 00:31:11,436
- Not especially.

668
00:31:11,469 --> 00:31:12,303
- Me neither.

669
00:31:12,337 --> 00:31:14,005
They're mean and stupid.

670
00:31:14,038 --> 00:31:15,640
- Don't say that, honey.

671
00:31:15,673 --> 00:31:17,875
Maggie's having some
trouble at school.

672
00:31:17,909 --> 00:31:19,677
Some of the kids
are picking on her.

673
00:31:19,711 --> 00:31:21,679
- You should just tell
them all to go to hell.

674
00:31:21,713 --> 00:31:23,014
- Uh, no, honey.

675
00:31:23,047 --> 00:31:25,416
You should be the bigger
person like we talked about.

676
00:31:25,450 --> 00:31:27,185
They'll follow your lead.

677
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:28,886
- She should stand
up for herself.

678
00:31:28,920 --> 00:31:30,722
- [Caroline] She should
turn the other cheek.

679
00:31:30,755 --> 00:31:32,257
- Why are they picking on you?

680
00:31:32,290 --> 00:31:34,192
Is it because your
mothers are lesbians?

681
00:31:34,225 --> 00:31:34,993
- No.

682
00:31:35,026 --> 00:31:36,561
It's because I'm purple.

683
00:31:36,594 --> 00:31:37,996
- What do you mean
you're purple?

684
00:31:38,029 --> 00:31:39,330
You mean you like purple?

685
00:31:39,364 --> 00:31:40,832
- I love purple.

686
00:31:40,865 --> 00:31:42,033
Purple is me.

687
00:31:42,066 --> 00:31:43,568
- Purple is I.

688
00:31:43,601 --> 00:31:44,535
- You're not purple.

689
00:31:44,569 --> 00:31:45,570
You're gray.

690
00:31:46,904 --> 00:31:49,007
- She's going through an
identity assertion phase.

691
00:31:49,040 --> 00:31:51,409
She identifies with
the color purple.

692
00:31:51,442 --> 00:31:54,779
Not the novel, the actual color.

693
00:31:54,812 --> 00:31:59,050
- The other kids say that
purple is dumb, so I'm dumb.

694
00:31:59,751 --> 00:32:00,885
- Purple is dumb.

695
00:32:05,990 --> 00:32:07,292
- Here we are.

696
00:32:07,325 --> 00:32:08,593
Say bye to Serena.

697
00:32:08,626 --> 00:32:10,061
- Bye to Serena.

698
00:32:14,098 --> 00:32:15,967
- The next time someone
says something mean to you,

699
00:32:16,000 --> 00:32:17,902
just tell them this.

700
00:32:17,935 --> 00:32:20,938
(Serena whispering)

701
00:32:23,374 --> 00:32:26,811
- [Caroline] Great,
we'll see you there.

702
00:32:28,179 --> 00:32:29,213
- [Maggie] Bye!

703
00:32:42,994 --> 00:32:44,128
- Ethan.

704
00:32:44,162 --> 00:32:45,496
Hi.

705
00:32:45,530 --> 00:32:48,666
What was it you
wanted to talk about?

706
00:32:49,834 --> 00:32:50,835
You're here?

707
00:32:54,072 --> 00:32:56,841
(upbeat music)

708
00:32:58,209 --> 00:32:59,977
- I'm excited to
meet your brother.

709
00:33:00,011 --> 00:33:01,979
- Half-brother.

710
00:33:02,013 --> 00:33:04,415
(upbeat music)

711
00:33:12,590 --> 00:33:13,391
- Serena!

712
00:33:24,302 --> 00:33:26,237
- You look different.

713
00:33:27,105 --> 00:33:28,139
- I'm Goth now.

714
00:33:28,172 --> 00:33:30,575
- Hi, I'm Caroline.

715
00:33:30,608 --> 00:33:32,377
We spoke on the
phone the other day.

716
00:33:32,410 --> 00:33:34,011
- Nice to meet you.

717
00:33:34,045 --> 00:33:35,113
How long have you
guys been friends?

718
00:33:35,146 --> 00:33:36,047
- We're not.

719
00:33:36,080 --> 00:33:37,348
We work together.

720
00:33:39,183 --> 00:33:40,084
- Cool.

721
00:33:40,118 --> 00:33:41,119
Are you a scientist, too?

722
00:33:41,152 --> 00:33:42,053
- Yes.

723
00:33:42,086 --> 00:33:44,422
As a matter of fact, I am.

724
00:33:44,455 --> 00:33:47,158
So, Ethan, what
brings you to LA?

725
00:33:47,191 --> 00:33:49,627
- Things aren't going so
well back home in Riverside.

726
00:33:49,660 --> 00:33:50,628
- Where are you staying?

727
00:33:50,661 --> 00:33:52,930
- Crashing at my
friend Damian's.

728
00:33:52,964 --> 00:33:57,168
He's got five other roommates
so I'm sleeping in the tub.

729
00:33:57,869 --> 00:33:59,170
- Is Damian in school?

730
00:33:59,203 --> 00:34:02,006
- No, he dropped out
to follow his passion.

731
00:34:02,039 --> 00:34:02,874
- And that is?

732
00:34:02,907 --> 00:34:03,808
- Body art.

733
00:34:05,243 --> 00:34:07,211
- Is that a type of dance?

734
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:10,882
- He lets me stay
with him if I let him

735
00:34:10,915 --> 00:34:12,917
practice his designs on me.

736
00:34:12,950 --> 00:34:14,419
He's a tattoo genius.

737
00:34:14,452 --> 00:34:16,754
- The genius spelled
despair incorrectly.

738
00:34:16,788 --> 00:34:19,323
- Yeah, that's why
he needs to practice.

739
00:34:19,357 --> 00:34:22,160
- Can't he practice
with a dictionary and
not on your flesh?

740
00:34:22,193 --> 00:34:23,127
- I don't mind the spelling.

741
00:34:23,161 --> 00:34:24,028
It's sort of ironic.

742
00:34:24,062 --> 00:34:25,229
- It's sort of retarded.

743
00:34:25,263 --> 00:34:26,297
- Serena.

744
00:34:27,198 --> 00:34:28,433
- Sorry.

745
00:34:28,466 --> 00:34:30,701
I feel that it's retarded.

746
00:34:33,704 --> 00:34:36,841
So what did you
want to talk about?

747
00:34:36,874 --> 00:34:38,176
- Mom and dad kicked me out.

748
00:34:38,209 --> 00:34:39,444
- Why?

749
00:34:39,477 --> 00:34:40,778
- The same reason
they kicked you out.

750
00:34:40,812 --> 00:34:42,213
- That was different.

751
00:34:42,246 --> 00:34:44,749
- I turned 18 last
week and they told me

752
00:34:44,782 --> 00:34:46,584
I could take care of myself.

753
00:34:46,617 --> 00:34:47,485
- Oh right.

754
00:34:52,123 --> 00:34:54,192
Happy birthday.

755
00:34:54,225 --> 00:34:56,627
- Listen, can I stay with you?

756
00:34:56,661 --> 00:34:58,396
Damian's place is
getting pretty cramped.

757
00:34:58,429 --> 00:35:00,364
- No, that would not work.

758
00:35:00,398 --> 00:35:02,266
- Just for a little while
so I save up some money.

759
00:35:02,300 --> 00:35:05,436
- Believe me, you're better
off at your friend Denny's.

760
00:35:05,470 --> 00:35:06,270
- Damian.

761
00:35:09,273 --> 00:35:11,609
- This should help you out.

762
00:35:13,644 --> 00:35:14,445
Take care.

763
00:35:15,379 --> 00:35:17,281
And get some blood work done,

764
00:35:17,315 --> 00:35:20,351
you've probably been
exposed to hepatitis.

765
00:35:20,384 --> 00:35:21,185
- Thanks.

766
00:35:24,689 --> 00:35:26,624
- Don't you think he should
be with family right now?

767
00:35:26,657 --> 00:35:30,695
- I hardly know him, and I have
the turtle to take care of.

768
00:35:30,728 --> 00:35:32,463
- There must be something
you feel comfortable

769
00:35:32,497 --> 00:35:33,698
doing to help.

770
00:35:37,335 --> 00:35:39,003
- Mm-mm.

771
00:35:39,036 --> 00:35:42,173
Everyone, meet our
new intern, Ethan.

772
00:35:46,077 --> 00:35:48,346
We've been short-staffed
since Laura killed herself

773
00:35:48,379 --> 00:35:50,348
and everyone quit.

774
00:35:50,381 --> 00:35:53,417
And we could use an
extra set of hands.

775
00:35:54,619 --> 00:35:57,154
- He doesn't look
very science-y.

776
00:35:57,188 --> 00:35:59,724
- Joan, please show Ethan
around and find him something

777
00:35:59,757 --> 00:36:02,360
to do that he can't
possibly mess up.

778
00:36:02,393 --> 00:36:05,162
- I'll show you a supply closet.

779
00:36:07,331 --> 00:36:09,400
- Look at you,
being a big sister.

780
00:36:09,433 --> 00:36:10,401
- Half-sister.

781
00:36:10,434 --> 00:36:11,969
- If this works out,
maybe you can invite him

782
00:36:12,003 --> 00:36:13,404
to come stay with you.

783
00:36:13,437 --> 00:36:15,439
- Maybe we can all hold hands

784
00:36:15,473 --> 00:36:18,242
and watch the sun set together.

785
00:36:19,410 --> 00:36:23,414
- I know you're being sarcastic,
but that sounds lovely.

786
00:36:24,215 --> 00:36:25,483
- Fleming's Salmonella
test came back negative.

787
00:36:25,516 --> 00:36:26,984
- You named the turtle Fleming?

788
00:36:27,018 --> 00:36:28,486
That is so cute.

789
00:36:28,519 --> 00:36:31,589
- Alexander Fleming
discovered penicillin.

790
00:36:31,622 --> 00:36:33,191
- It's a distinguished name.

791
00:36:33,224 --> 00:36:34,792
- Did you get a
chance to look at my--

792
00:36:34,825 --> 00:36:37,261
- There were errors
in your report.

793
00:36:37,295 --> 00:36:38,062
- Really?

794
00:36:38,095 --> 00:36:38,963
I checked all--

795
00:36:38,996 --> 00:36:41,299
- [Serena] I made revisions.

796
00:36:43,200 --> 00:36:47,138
- Serena, don't you think
you were harsh with Ellen?

797
00:36:47,171 --> 00:36:49,440
- I treated her
like a professional.

798
00:36:49,473 --> 00:36:51,209
- That report must have
been 40 pages long.

799
00:36:51,242 --> 00:36:52,209
That's a lot of work.

800
00:36:52,243 --> 00:36:53,811
- Yes, it is.

801
00:36:53,844 --> 00:36:55,713
- Where are you going?

802
00:36:55,746 --> 00:36:56,981
- To the bathroom.

803
00:36:57,014 --> 00:36:58,683
Would you like to come
with and supervise

804
00:36:58,716 --> 00:37:00,618
how I treat the toilet?

805
00:37:04,722 --> 00:37:07,892
(door clicking open)

806
00:37:07,925 --> 00:37:10,728
(Ellen sniffling)

807
00:37:21,038 --> 00:37:23,608
(water gushing)

808
00:37:28,312 --> 00:37:29,614
- It's nothing.

809
00:38:03,881 --> 00:38:04,782
- Good job.

810
00:38:15,092 --> 00:38:16,727
- [Caroline] It doesn't
have to be perfect.

811
00:38:16,761 --> 00:38:18,195
- They better not
touch anything.

812
00:38:18,229 --> 00:38:20,064
- Just remember why
you're doing this.

813
00:38:20,097 --> 00:38:21,732
- Because you made me.

814
00:38:21,766 --> 00:38:24,068
- Because it's important
to let people in.

815
00:38:24,101 --> 00:38:25,703
Take an interest
in your colleagues

816
00:38:25,736 --> 00:38:28,172
and let them know
they're appreciated.

817
00:38:28,205 --> 00:38:29,573
- Uh-huh.

818
00:38:29,607 --> 00:38:30,841
(buzzer buzzing)

819
00:38:30,875 --> 00:38:32,677
- Wait, wait, wait, wait!

820
00:38:32,710 --> 00:38:33,844
I want to watch.

821
00:38:33,878 --> 00:38:35,379
Hide the iPad by the table.

822
00:38:35,413 --> 00:38:36,414
- Seriously?

823
00:38:36,447 --> 00:38:38,015
- Put your Bluetooth in.

824
00:38:38,049 --> 00:38:39,684
I can help you during dinner.

825
00:38:39,717 --> 00:38:41,018
- Okay, Cyrano.

826
00:38:42,953 --> 00:38:44,889
(buzzer buzzing)

827
00:38:44,922 --> 00:38:46,223
- Hi!

828
00:38:46,257 --> 00:38:48,426
- Welcome, Joan.

829
00:38:48,459 --> 00:38:49,560
- [Caroline] Invite her in.

830
00:38:49,593 --> 00:38:51,429
- Please, come in.

831
00:38:51,462 --> 00:38:53,831
Uh, actually, I don't allow...

832
00:38:55,800 --> 00:38:57,735
Would you mind taking
off your shoes?

833
00:38:57,768 --> 00:38:58,769
- I wiped them.

834
00:38:58,803 --> 00:38:59,670
- It's just--

835
00:38:59,704 --> 00:39:00,638
- [Caroline] Just let it go.

836
00:39:00,671 --> 00:39:02,840
It is too late to call 911.

837
00:39:02,873 --> 00:39:03,941
- Would you like a drink?

838
00:39:03,974 --> 00:39:04,775
- Sure!

839
00:39:08,779 --> 00:39:11,315
- [Caroline] Try
to bond with her.

840
00:39:11,348 --> 00:39:15,152
- So, we're just a couple
of women scientists.

841
00:39:17,054 --> 00:39:17,855
- Yep.

842
00:39:19,557 --> 00:39:20,958
- [Caroline] Keep it going.

843
00:39:20,991 --> 00:39:23,828
- In such a
male-dominated field.

844
00:39:23,861 --> 00:39:24,662
- Yes.

845
00:39:28,365 --> 00:39:30,801
- Make it more personal.

846
00:39:30,835 --> 00:39:32,403
- When do you menstruate?

847
00:39:32,436 --> 00:39:34,372
Maybe our cycles have
synced due to all the time

848
00:39:34,405 --> 00:39:35,673
we spend together in the lab.

849
00:39:35,706 --> 00:39:37,007
- Ha-ha-ha-ha-ha!

850
00:39:39,844 --> 00:39:40,611
Sorry.

851
00:39:43,047 --> 00:39:45,950
(buzzer buzzing)

852
00:39:46,817 --> 00:39:48,219
- [Caroline] Talk!

853
00:39:50,888 --> 00:39:52,423
Serena!

854
00:39:52,456 --> 00:39:55,126
- Why don't you each tell
me about your hobbies?

855
00:39:55,159 --> 00:39:56,961
- [Caroline] Good.

856
00:39:56,994 --> 00:39:58,963
- Sandra and I like to
leave Hunter with a sitter

857
00:39:58,996 --> 00:40:01,098
and go antiquing
in Palm Springs.

858
00:40:01,132 --> 00:40:03,734
- [Caroline] Nod and smile.

859
00:40:03,768 --> 00:40:06,203
- What about you, Joan?

860
00:40:06,237 --> 00:40:08,639
- I've become prolific
in slam poetry

861
00:40:08,672 --> 00:40:11,475
since discovering I was adopted.

862
00:40:11,509 --> 00:40:12,877
- [Caroline] Are you nodding?

863
00:40:12,910 --> 00:40:15,379
- I recently joined the
Quidditch team on campus.

864
00:40:15,412 --> 00:40:16,280
- Wow!

865
00:40:16,313 --> 00:40:17,481
- [Dr Hamilton] That's great.

866
00:40:17,515 --> 00:40:18,983
- Quidditch?

867
00:40:19,016 --> 00:40:21,585
- The game from Harry Potter.

868
00:40:23,654 --> 00:40:27,258
- [Caroline] I can't
believe they have that.

869
00:40:28,459 --> 00:40:29,894
- Thank you for coming.

870
00:40:29,927 --> 00:40:30,795
- Thanks for having us.

871
00:40:30,828 --> 00:40:33,063
- We should to this again, soon.

872
00:40:33,097 --> 00:40:34,765
- Good night!

873
00:40:34,799 --> 00:40:36,100
- [Caroline] Great job!

874
00:40:36,133 --> 00:40:37,768
- Please just tell me
I don't have to attend

875
00:40:37,802 --> 00:40:38,936
a Quidditch match.

876
00:40:38,969 --> 00:40:40,638
- Baby steps.

877
00:40:40,671 --> 00:40:42,072
I'm really proud of you!

878
00:40:42,106 --> 00:40:43,340
- [Serena] Uh!

879
00:40:43,374 --> 00:40:44,141
- Night!

880
00:40:44,175 --> 00:40:45,676
- [Serena] Mm-hm.

881
00:40:47,011 --> 00:40:49,880
- [Sarah] Did you just coach
her through an entire dinner?

882
00:40:49,914 --> 00:40:51,782
- She says the funniest things.

883
00:40:51,816 --> 00:40:53,484
I mean not a lot of
people could get away

884
00:40:53,517 --> 00:40:55,486
with the stuff she says.

885
00:40:55,519 --> 00:40:57,154
- She can't get away with it.

886
00:40:57,188 --> 00:40:59,156
That's why they
assigned you to her.

887
00:40:59,190 --> 00:41:03,260
And why you're spending
so much time with her.

888
00:41:03,294 --> 00:41:07,531
- I don't know how to explain
it, but I really need this.

889
00:41:08,132 --> 00:41:09,867
(toys crashing)

890
00:41:09,900 --> 00:41:10,901
- [Maggie] Mommy!

891
00:41:10,935 --> 00:41:12,770
- [Sarah] I'll go.

892
00:41:12,803 --> 00:41:14,138
Coming sweetie!

893
00:41:18,108 --> 00:41:20,611
- Dr Wolfe, the last
formula we tried worked.

894
00:41:20,644 --> 00:41:23,747
- It killed 97.3% of the
virilis in the isolated sample.

895
00:41:23,781 --> 00:41:25,549
We're running it
again to make sure.

896
00:41:25,583 --> 00:41:27,218
- Shit, it worked!

897
00:41:29,153 --> 00:41:30,421
- Oh.

898
00:41:30,454 --> 00:41:34,024
- Let's double and triple
check these results.

899
00:41:34,058 --> 00:41:35,159
- [Dr Hamilton]
That was strange.

900
00:41:35,192 --> 00:41:36,427
- [Joan] I don't
know, I liked it.

901
00:41:36,460 --> 00:41:37,761
- [Ellen] Me too.

902
00:41:45,870 --> 00:41:47,271
- Congratulations.

903
00:41:48,873 --> 00:41:49,673
- Thanks.

904
00:41:54,278 --> 00:41:55,613
- To teamwork.

905
00:41:55,646 --> 00:41:57,281
- We just drank.

906
00:41:57,314 --> 00:42:00,017
- Can you admit that improved
morale may have contributed

907
00:42:00,050 --> 00:42:01,652
to today's victory?

908
00:42:01,685 --> 00:42:04,288
Come on, I really
like cheersing.

909
00:42:05,689 --> 00:42:07,491
- Alright, I admit it.

910
00:42:11,028 --> 00:42:12,162
- To sensitivity!

911
00:42:12,196 --> 00:42:15,032
- Now, you're pushing it.

912
00:42:15,065 --> 00:42:17,968
To Fleming, the
turtle and the man.

913
00:42:23,540 --> 00:42:25,342
How's Maggie?

914
00:42:25,376 --> 00:42:27,011
- She's tougher than I was.

915
00:42:27,044 --> 00:42:29,146
- You were teased in school too?

916
00:42:29,179 --> 00:42:30,414
- Who wasn't?

917
00:42:30,447 --> 00:42:34,418
- Did they pick on you
because you're a lesbian?

918
00:42:34,585 --> 00:42:35,553
- I was fat.

919
00:42:40,090 --> 00:42:42,226
My mom told me to kill
them with kindness

920
00:42:42,259 --> 00:42:45,296
so no matter what they said
to me, I was nice back,

921
00:42:45,329 --> 00:42:46,964
and that took all the
fun out of teasing me

922
00:42:46,997 --> 00:42:48,399
so they left me alone.

923
00:42:48,432 --> 00:42:51,201
By high school, I
was class secretary

924
00:42:51,235 --> 00:42:54,305
and head of the
homecoming committee.

925
00:42:56,273 --> 00:42:58,275
- Didn't you ever just
want to tell them off?

926
00:42:58,309 --> 00:43:02,513
- Why give them the
satisfaction of seeing me upset?

927
00:43:03,681 --> 00:43:05,282
I know you don't like
talking about it,

928
00:43:05,316 --> 00:43:07,318
but your parents, Ethan?

929
00:43:15,326 --> 00:43:17,428
- My mother is retarded
and my stepfather

930
00:43:17,461 --> 00:43:18,429
is a giant asshole.

931
00:43:18,462 --> 00:43:19,263
- Right.

932
00:43:21,999 --> 00:43:24,435
So, your stepfather...

933
00:43:24,468 --> 00:43:26,070
- Glenn.

934
00:43:26,103 --> 00:43:30,307
When my father left, my
mother was destroyed.

935
00:43:30,975 --> 00:43:32,142
Then she met Glenn.

936
00:43:35,079 --> 00:43:36,313
Doesn't that name
sound like someone

937
00:43:36,347 --> 00:43:38,716
you just want to
punch in the face?

938
00:43:38,749 --> 00:43:40,284
- What about John Glenn?

939
00:43:40,317 --> 00:43:42,486
- It's different as a last name.

940
00:43:42,519 --> 00:43:45,189
Glenns would eat vomit and
tell you that they liked it

941
00:43:45,222 --> 00:43:47,658
if you told them it was
a delicacy that required

942
00:43:47,691 --> 00:43:49,927
a refined palate to appreciate.

943
00:43:49,960 --> 00:43:53,163
Glenns walk around in their
boxers and wink at you

944
00:43:53,197 --> 00:43:57,201
if you walk in on him
and your mom having sex.

945
00:43:57,234 --> 00:43:59,269
- That's very specific.

946
00:43:59,303 --> 00:44:02,039
- After Ethan was
born and I turned 18,

947
00:44:02,072 --> 00:44:04,375
they said I could
take care of myself.

948
00:44:04,408 --> 00:44:06,543
I put myself through college.

949
00:44:06,577 --> 00:44:07,544
I didn't visit.

950
00:44:07,578 --> 00:44:09,113
I wasn't welcome.

951
00:44:10,547 --> 00:44:12,750
I barely recognized Ethan.

952
00:44:14,284 --> 00:44:16,353
- Now, poor Ethan is going
through the same thing.

953
00:44:16,387 --> 00:44:17,955
- I don't understand it.

954
00:44:17,988 --> 00:44:21,258
I was like this remnant of
my mother's shitty marriage,

955
00:44:21,291 --> 00:44:24,461
but I can't believe that Glenn
would kick out his own son.

956
00:44:24,495 --> 00:44:28,132
- Your mother kicked
out her own daughter.

957
00:44:29,400 --> 00:44:30,968
Didn't you say you
got married young?

958
00:44:31,001 --> 00:44:32,903
- My biology professor.

959
00:44:34,304 --> 00:44:36,607
I was his favorite student.

960
00:44:37,474 --> 00:44:39,309
- And then what?

961
00:44:39,343 --> 00:44:42,613
- He found another
favorite student.

962
00:44:42,646 --> 00:44:45,115
- So you felt abandoned
by your parents

963
00:44:45,149 --> 00:44:48,318
and the person you turned to
for comfort abandoned you too?

964
00:44:48,352 --> 00:44:51,021
- Well, it taught me
to rely on myself.

965
00:44:51,055 --> 00:44:55,292
- I can see why it's hard
for you to trust people.

966
00:44:56,493 --> 00:44:59,029
- I never thought
of it that way.

967
00:45:00,364 --> 00:45:02,499
Did you just therapy me?

968
00:45:02,533 --> 00:45:03,767
Sneaky.

969
00:45:03,801 --> 00:45:05,135
- You liked it.

970
00:45:09,840 --> 00:45:11,775
This is getting gloomy.

971
00:45:11,809 --> 00:45:13,444
What do you normally
do to celebrate

972
00:45:13,477 --> 00:45:15,646
a major scientific breakthrough?

973
00:45:15,679 --> 00:45:17,047
- Oh, I'm usually just annoyed

974
00:45:17,081 --> 00:45:19,216
that I didn't figure
it out sooner.

975
00:45:19,249 --> 00:45:22,853
- I'm not going to
acknowledge you said that.

976
00:45:22,886 --> 00:45:26,323
(Caroline laughs)

977
00:45:26,356 --> 00:45:27,124
Whiskey.

978
00:45:29,626 --> 00:45:32,096
I have a surprise for you.

979
00:45:32,129 --> 00:45:33,897
You're going to love it.

980
00:45:33,931 --> 00:45:35,232
- Okay.

981
00:45:35,265 --> 00:45:36,600
- This is going to be fun.

982
00:45:36,633 --> 00:45:37,701
Okay.

983
00:45:37,734 --> 00:45:39,536
You know how you never get
to see the end of movies

984
00:45:39,570 --> 00:45:41,371
because of your anger
management problem?

985
00:45:41,405 --> 00:45:44,475
- I'd say it's because of the
completely intolerable nature

986
00:45:44,508 --> 00:45:46,143
of the average moviegoer.

987
00:45:46,176 --> 00:45:47,411
- Right.

988
00:45:47,444 --> 00:45:49,146
So I was thinking,
how many great movies

989
00:45:49,179 --> 00:45:51,749
have you never
seen the ending to?

990
00:45:51,782 --> 00:45:55,986
We are going to watch movies
all the way through to the end!

991
00:45:59,690 --> 00:46:00,657
Where is your TV?

992
00:46:00,691 --> 00:46:03,127
- I don't have a TV.

993
00:46:03,160 --> 00:46:05,796
(soft music)

994
00:46:05,829 --> 00:46:08,732
She had the heart of the
ocean the entire time.

995
00:46:08,765 --> 00:46:11,835
And then she just
threw it back in.

996
00:46:11,869 --> 00:46:13,737
The explorer's search
was completely in vain

997
00:46:13,770 --> 00:46:15,105
and I'm pretty sure if
they'd tried harder,

998
00:46:15,139 --> 00:46:17,574
they both could have fit on
that piece of drift wood.

999
00:46:17,608 --> 00:46:20,144
(soft music)

1000
00:46:23,180 --> 00:46:24,781
They had such a
beautiful friendship.

1001
00:46:24,815 --> 00:46:27,618
I can't believe they
chose to die like that.

1002
00:46:27,651 --> 00:46:29,620
- They ran out of options.

1003
00:46:29,653 --> 00:46:32,322
They didn't want to go to jail.

1004
00:46:32,356 --> 00:46:35,626
- They finally found their
freedom and would rather die

1005
00:46:35,659 --> 00:46:38,195
than let anyone take it away.

1006
00:46:39,730 --> 00:46:40,931
- That's deep.

1007
00:46:40,964 --> 00:46:42,733
(suspenseful music) Ah!

1008
00:46:42,766 --> 00:46:45,769
(Caroline laughing)

1009
00:46:49,206 --> 00:46:50,374
Selfie!

1010
00:46:50,407 --> 00:46:52,543
- That's not a word.

1011
00:46:52,576 --> 00:46:54,044
(energetic music)

1012
00:46:54,077 --> 00:46:55,379
Oh my God.

1013
00:46:55,412 --> 00:46:56,947
Is this fight club?

1014
00:46:56,980 --> 00:46:58,215
Are you really me?

1015
00:46:58,248 --> 00:46:59,950
- I'm not you.

1016
00:46:59,983 --> 00:47:02,252
- You can't be me!

1017
00:47:02,286 --> 00:47:05,556
- You're a really
belligerent drunk.

1018
00:47:05,589 --> 00:47:06,623
- Ahhh!

1019
00:47:06,657 --> 00:47:08,025
Fight Club!

1020
00:47:08,058 --> 00:47:10,761
(upbeat music)

1021
00:47:12,596 --> 00:47:13,964
- Staring contest.

1022
00:47:17,901 --> 00:47:19,803
- You have pretty eyes.

1023
00:47:50,267 --> 00:47:51,868
Did you know that
Bruce Willis is dead

1024
00:47:51,902 --> 00:47:54,037
the entire time in
The Sixth Sense?

1025
00:47:54,071 --> 00:47:55,539
- Yeah.

1026
00:47:55,572 --> 00:47:56,974
- What an amazing twist.

1027
00:47:57,007 --> 00:48:00,077
I never would've known if
Caroline hadn't shown me.

1028
00:48:00,110 --> 00:48:01,245
(laughing)

1029
00:48:02,012 --> 00:48:02,980
- What is it?

1030
00:48:03,013 --> 00:48:04,014
- Huh?

1031
00:48:04,047 --> 00:48:04,948
Oh nothing.

1032
00:48:06,116 --> 00:48:07,517
(laughing)

1033
00:48:07,551 --> 00:48:08,852
- Come on, what?

1034
00:48:08,885 --> 00:48:11,054
- Just something Caroline said.

1035
00:48:11,088 --> 00:48:12,589
(laughing)

1036
00:48:12,623 --> 00:48:13,590
- We've done repeat tests

1037
00:48:13,624 --> 00:48:14,892
and we've still been
getting good results.

1038
00:48:14,925 --> 00:48:16,059
- That's great.

1039
00:48:16,093 --> 00:48:16,894
Thanks.

1040
00:48:18,061 --> 00:48:19,963
- There are a couple
of human samples

1041
00:48:19,997 --> 00:48:23,967
that are still not responding
as quickly to the new formula.

1042
00:48:24,701 --> 00:48:25,469
- Dr Wolfe?

1043
00:48:26,637 --> 00:48:28,805
- It's probably
just a sensor error.

1044
00:48:28,839 --> 00:48:29,740
Let's keep an eye on it.

1045
00:48:29,773 --> 00:48:30,908
Thanks for letting me know.

1046
00:48:30,941 --> 00:48:33,477
- Are you all right?

1047
00:48:33,510 --> 00:48:34,678
